 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caenn>Caenn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#333333>(2/18/03 1:25:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=94>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: idiot socialists</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Rather, I believe that America should be the world's merchant and allow capitalism and its buisnesses to invest in the economies of other nations, which will cause their economy to grow. I am a firm believer in globalization..<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Are you prepared to allow Saddam Hussein to have control of the economy that will ensue in Iraq when that country begins trading on one of the world's largest oil reserves?  Do you really think that he is the best man for the job?  I don't.  I mean, you have to know where any riches his country were to take in would go.  Even if you look at the Iraq situation purely from an economic perspective, Saddam Hussein has to be removed from the equation.  <br>
<br>
I don't disagree that the US should be the world's merchant and not it's policing force.  But I think that is an over-simplification.  When talking about governments and political systems and foreign relations there are so many more aspects than just trade.  (Incidentally, this is why I am not a Libertarian :P).  What merchant in his right mind would do business with a tyrant like Saddam Hussein if he had a choice?  <br>
<br>
We could turn our backs and refuse to trade with Iraq, as we have been doing for the past 10 years, but what will that get us?  Nothing.  No money coming in from or going out to the people of Iraq, the problems with Hussein doing nothing but continuing to fester, the possibility of weapons getting into the hands of people like Osama bin Laden, the people of Iraq continuing to starve and be without medical care, etc etc etc.<br>
<br>
The United States government has the responsibility to provide its citizenry with an environment in which people can prosper (not to make its citizenry prosperous, which is what some would have you believe...just had to take that shot).  I don't believe that an Iraq with Saddam Hussein as its leader constitutes and environment in which <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>anybody</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can prosper.  The government has to ensure that it is doing business with the right people for the right reasons, and the government has the means to ensure that this happens.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I suppose the last reason why I am against the war is because I personally am not willing to go to war.  I will not fight, and because I won't fight, I shall not cast a vote for another man to fight in my place&quot; -That Guy From the Patriot. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The idea that &quot;what's good for me has to be good for you&quot; is not a new one.  It is a statement of Kant's &quot;categorical imperative&quot;, just fyi, and it is a perfectly valid stance.  Most rational people subscribe to this line of thinking (myself included, though my rationality could be questioned :P), and it is not selfish in the least.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>even though the arguements that you have declared my first post's scenarios &quot;stock anti-war slogans/reasons&quot; (not an incorrect assessment) they still are in the very least logical (however flawed the logic may be) reasons to not want to go to war with Iraq. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, of course they are logical...at least on the surface.  Which is why they appeal to so many people.  The problem is that so many people allow their responsibility to question to completely consume their responsibility to be well informed.  They do not care to look any deeper than the surface.  They do not ask &quot;why&quot; it is that all these bad things will happen, they just adopt a mantra and run with it.  This is a disservice to themselves and to this country, in my opinion.<br>
<br>
If you've ever seen or read some of the interviews with the &quot;hard-core&quot; anit-war people, it is very plainly (and very sadly, imo) evident that they haven't a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>*clue*</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> what is going on in the world.  They seem to look at this purely as a chance to rebel.  Unfortunately I don't have time at the moment to look for a few quotes from these people, but I'll do so later just to show you what I mean. <p><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
