<br>
Caenn:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The idea that &quot;what's good for me has to be good for you&quot; is not a new one. It is a statement of Kant's &quot;categorical imperative&quot;, just fyi, and it is a perfectly valid stance. Most rational people subscribe to this line of thinking (myself included, though my rationality could be questioned :P), and it is not selfish in the least.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Wanted to clarify something about the Categorical Imperative of which Caenn clearly is abreast, but those unfamiliar with Kant might not realise after reading the reference to his CI.  Kant said we should not act but that our actions conform to what we would have be universal law.  I.e., the stress is on discovering good universal laws first and conforming to them, rather than acting first and formulating universal laws to conform to our actions (which would be more Nietzschean than Kantian). =)<br>
<br>
Caenn:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> If you've ever seen or read some of the interviews with the &quot;hard-core&quot; anit-war people, it is very plainly (and very sadly, imo) evident that they haven't a *clue* what is going on in the world. They seem to look at this purely as a chance to rebel. Unfortunately I don't have time at the moment to look for a few quotes from these people, but I'll do so later just to show you what I mean. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
